what /mnt dirs are available to me

Claude responded: 
Four dirs under /mnt:

/mnt/project — empty
/mnt/skills — skill definitions (public, private, examples, user)
/mnt/transcripts — conversation transcripts
/mnt/user-data

what is the difference between those 4 dirs. when are they used. What is visible or writeable by other chats

#********************
/mnt/user-data/ — your files, this session
Cross-chat visibility: no — each conversation gets its own isolated instance

uploads/ — files you drag into chat; read-only to me, scoped to this conversation
outputs/ — where I write files you can download; writable
tool_results/ — internal scratch used by tools

#********************
/mnt/skills/ — behavior instructions, injected by Anthropic/your org
Writable in principle but don't write here — changes won't persist across sessions and could corrupt skill definitions
Cross-chat visibility: yes — same skills are mounted in every chat in your account/org

public/ — Anthropic-provided skills (docx, pdf, xlsx, etc.)
user/ — your org's custom skills (e.g. google-cpp-style)
examples/ — example/template skills


#********************
/mnt/transcripts/ — read-only, currently empty
Intended to hold past conversation transcripts when that feature is active
Read-only filesystem — nothing can write here
Cross-chat visibility: potentially yes (shared read access), but empty right now

#********************
/mnt/project/ — writable, currently empty
This is your project-scoped shared storage — files here persist across chats within the same Claude project
This is the one dir where work genuinely survives between sessions within a project
Cross-chat visibility: yes, within the same project


#********************
Summary of cross-chat persistence:
Dir               Writable        Persists_across_chats
/mnt/user-data/   outputs yes     No — per-conversation
/mnt/skills/      technically yes No — read from config
/mnt/transcripts/ No              Read-only
/mnt/project/     Yes             Yes — within project


can I force you to always present files you modify, to be in /mnt/project

Claude responded: 

You can't force it at the filesystem level — I can write anywhere that's writable, and there's no mount-level redirect. 
But you can get the same effect two ways:

1. User Preferences instruction (what you already have)
Add something like:
"Always save output files to /mnt/project/ instead of /mnt/user-data/outputs/. Always call present_files after modifying any file in /mnt/project/."
That's a standing instruction I'll follow in every chat in this project. 
It's not enforced mechanically but it's reliable.

2. Per-session reminder
Just tell me at the start of a chat: "work in /mnt/project today." I'll follow it for the session.

#*************************************************************************
No — user preferences apply account-wide, but the /mnt/project/ mount is project-specific. If I tried to write to /mnt/project/ in a chat outside this project, that path either won't exist or will be a different project's directory.

So the constraint is the filesystem, not the instruction system:

Context	Instruction followable	/mnt/project/ available
This project	Yes	Yes
Another project	           Yes	Yes, but different dir
No project (plain chat)	   Yes	Likely empty/absent

What you can do globally: Add a preference like:
"Always save output files to /mnt/project/ if it exists and is writable, otherwise fall back to /mnt/user-data/outputs/. Always call present_files after modifying any file."

That works everywhere — I check, use /mnt/project/ when available, fall back gracefully when not. The present_files part applies universally regardless.

Here's text you can paste into Settings → Profile → User Preferences:Here's text you can paste into Settings → Profile → User Preferences:

"Always save output files to /mnt/project/ if it exists and is writable, otherwise fall back to /mnt/user-data/outputs/. Always call present_files after creating or modifying any file."

Short, unambiguous, works in all contexts.
#*************************************************************************
